Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["CoherenceOrderFiltrationSuperoperator", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.544379401151694*^9, 
  3.544379435793702*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6f6b1ca8-77e4-491e-973f-\
291e3c4646b5"],

Cell["\<\
CoherenceOrderFiltrationSuperoperator is used to filter out the components of \
the spin density operator which belong to a set of coherence orders. This can \
be a quick way to emulate the effect of phase cycling, or field gradient \
combinations. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.544380036976902*^9, 
  3.544380081045005*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b0684e54-15fe-4d51-a5cb-\
a14f4cac90ee"],

Cell["\<\
In general, the syntax CoherenceOrderFiltrationSuperoperator[spins,pvals] \
defines filtration by the set of coherence orders pvals, belonging to the \
spins defined in spins. If the specification spins is omitted, all of the \
spins in the current SpinSystem are used. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.588071468677699*^9, 
  3.588071555039419*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"56bb19f6-4417-4a40-af01-\
1c799be168c2"],

Cell["\<\
For example, the syntax CoherenceOrderFiltrationSuperoperator[p] defines \
filtration by the single coherence order p, belonging to all spins (in the \
case below, there are 3 spins, labelled {1,2,3}).\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.544380089495572*^9, 3.54438013382041*^9}, {
  3.588071564576669*^9, 3.58807158169713*^9}, {3.722565877644977*^9, 
  3.722565897302583*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"df461fc2-e172-4f7b-b11f-\
11445c2c7bc4"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

